description:
The NVIDIA RTX 5070 is here but they timed this launch and reviews perfectly, right before the AMD RX 9070 XT and RX 9070 reviews go live tomorrow.  It feels like desperation but is the RTX 5070 better than we expected and how will it translate into availability and actual pricing?  

TIMESTAMPS:
0:00 - We Need to Talk...
1:27 - The RTX 5070 Review
2:31 - RTX 5070 Pricing, Specs, Availability
3:37 - Power Consumption @ 1440p
5:00 - Power Consumption @ 4K
5:50 - RTX 5070 Founder's Edition Detailed
7:05 - Inferior Cooling 
7:52 - 1440p & 4K Gaming Benchmarks (Raster)
13:27 - Ray Tracing Framerates 
16:41 - An RTX 4070 Super Clone...but Worse?
18:21 - The RX 9070 Question

GET MERCH https://hwcstore.com
SUBSCRIBE https://bit.ly/SubHWC

Review unit provided free of charge by NVIDIA. As per Hardware Canucks guidelines, no review direction was received from manufacturer. As an Amazon Associate we earn from qualifying purchases. 

Follow us for more updates!
Twitter https://bit.ly/HWC_Twitter
FaceBook https://bit.ly/HWC_Facebook
Instagram https://bit.ly/HWC_Instagram

comments.text:
Mindshare over matter- they care more that people perceive their cards as being superior when in fact it is only the $1,000 plus cards that can barely reach manageable framerates in native 4k with max settings and RT. Of course that new AI tech works best on those expensive cards and gets much worse the further down the stack you go.

The problem is that most people think that since they have a green sticker on the side that says Nvidia they convince themselves that their Corolla has the same performance as a Supra.

I get you, and while production costs have increased, so has the market size.
Literally 5 years ago, and for much of the lifespan of the graphics card market, we would routinely experience 30-50% increases in performance per generation with prices dropping as the population of PC gamers grew.
Hell, there used to be skits on both the internet and tv about the generational uplift being so massive and common that you'd see an advertisement for a part, buy it, and then when you got home it was already out of date.

comments.author: @yeshyk3694

comments.text:
R9 Nano happened almost a decade ago, 2 slot 1 fan short 175W card, Nvidia (partners) did similarly with GTX 1080, 2070, 3060Ti, and a single rare late 4070 model, all of these are 180-200W and fit into less than a "liter" of space, so > 200 "Watts per liter"

AMD (partners) did the same with Powercolor 5700 ITX and Vega 56 Nano e.g., but nothing for 6650XT or 7600XT 

 (R9 nano is 15.5x4x11 e.g. which comes to about 0.7 Liter, so 175 divided by 0.7 is 250W/L)

the 9070 / XT isn't 180W, but with this metric, at 220W and 300W, then they should be like 20% and 66% larger. The 9070XT Reaper is close enough...but the 9070 has nothing

I don't know why GPU companies can't just reuse 8-10 year old GPU designs, and I don't know why after 8-10 years we are mostly getting less "dense"/"efficient" cooler designs


Another example is Galax 1070 Katana


It would be interesting if you had some sort of size-TDP-temp-noise normalized testing

comments.text:
@tomthomas3499 We can have both higher and lower TDP models. I don't know if lower TDP models have really been done, I know GTX 950 had 75W pcie only variants. Would just be cooler (lol) if we could just buy cooler like we do for CPU and choose PL accordingly...

GTX 1080/Ti had compact variants and large OC'able variants e.g.

High power limits often lead to diminishing returns, which is why I'm adamant about smaller cards; you can generally undervolt >25% TDP for maybe a 5% loss in performance. In this case, 5% performance is worth smaller quieter cooler card?

Also, card size != cooling capacity. The 5080 FE vs the 5090 FE is a good example. Another example could be the Galax 1070 Katana, despite being almost half the size of the FE, Techspot's review of it says it runs better...

It's not any different than a well-built 14" (or even 13" now) gaming laptop outdoing a 16" laptop in my eyes (and yes it happens unfortunately)
